export const VERIFIED_BRIEFS = [{"id":"resurrection-minimal-facts","topic":"The minimal-facts method for the resurrection","tags":["resurrection","minimal facts","habermas","licona","best explanation","historical method","rose from the dead","prove resurrection","disciples","evidence","case for the resurrection","historical evidence","rose again"],"framing":"When someone objects that the resurrection can't be argued because it just rests on the Bible, the strongest reply is the 'minimal facts' method (Habermas and Licona): don't ask the sceptic to grant the Gospels' reliability — build only on a few facts that even critical, non-Christian scholars already grant, then argue that the resurrection is the best explanation of them. It is an inference to the best explanation, the way a historian weighs rival hypotheses, never a mathematical proof. The honest limit to concede openly: it removes the HISTORICAL excuse for unbelief but cannot by itself compel someone whose worldview rules out miracles in advance. As Dale Allison presses, how one weighs the probabilities depends heavily on the priors one brings — which is precisely why the argument's force is to shift the burden onto that anti-miracle assumption, not to leave the resurrection a matter of taste. The argument's real power is that it leans on what the critics themselves grant. For the full case with sources, point to the Evidence Library's minimal-facts essay.","from":["library/minimalfacts.html","docs/book-research/case-for-the-resurrection-of-jesus.md"]},{"id":"resurrection-creed-dating","topic":"The early 1 Corinthians 15 creed and its dating","tags":["resurrection","creed","1 corinthians 15","dating","early","legend","paul received","how soon written","disciples","eyewitness","how early","decades later","first written"],"framing":"For the resurrection, lead with the early creed, not 'the Gospels say so.' In 1 Corinthians 15:3-7 Paul quotes a fixed tradition he says he 'received' and 'delivered' — that Christ died, was buried, was raised, and appeared. Critical scholars across the spectrum date this creed to within a few years of the crucifixion (roughly 2-5 years); the stronger 'within months' claim should be attributed to those who argue it (e.g. James Dunn), not asserted in our own voice. That early dating is the whole point: it is far too early for legend to have done its slow work, which answers the 'it was written decades later' objection. Keep the conclusion modest — 'the disciples sincerely believed they saw the risen Jesus,' never 'it is proven they saw him.' For the scholarship, point to the creed/dating essay.","from":["library/minimalfacts.html","docs/book-research/case-for-the-resurrection-of-jesus.md"]},{"id":"resurrection-empty-tomb","topic":"The empty tomb — the case and its honest limits","tags":["resurrection","empty tomb","jerusalem","women witnesses","stolen body","burial","tomb","body","grave","no body","missing body"],"framing":"The empty tomb is a genuine strand of the case, but the SOFT one — present it as such, not as bulletproof. Three honest supports: the resurrection was proclaimed in Jerusalem, where opponents needed only to produce the body and did not; the earliest Jewish counter-claim ('the disciples stole him') itself concedes the tomb was empty; and all four Gospels make women the first witnesses, which an invented story in that culture would not have done. The honest limit to state plainly: the empty tomb is granted by fewer scholars than the crucifixion or the disciples' experiences, and the often-quoted 'about three-quarters of scholars' figure is Habermas's own tally of the literature he has read, not an audited poll — so never inflate 'a majority' into 'virtually all.' Concede the observation, never more than the evidence gives. For detail, point to the empty-tomb essay.","from":["library/emptytomb.html","docs/book-research/case-for-the-resurrection-of-jesus.md"]},{"id":"resurrection-hallucination-vision","topic":"Hallucination and vision theories of the appearances","tags":["resurrection","hallucination","vision","grief","bereavement","ehrman","appearances","saw jesus","disciples","hallucinate","seeing things","imagined","mass hallucination","visions of jesus"],"framing":"'They hallucinated' is the objection serious critics actually press, so answer its strongest form, don't caricature it. At its best (Bart Ehrman) it is not lone hallucination but shared bereavement or religious visions — like reported group apparitions. Two things resist that: the witnesses include people with no grief and no expectation — Paul, a hostile persecutor, and James, a sceptic who had thought Jesus was out of his mind — whereas grief-visions arise among those already longing for the one they lost; and no such vision tradition has ever produced a community convinced a particular person was bodily raised and then willing to suffer and die for it. Keep the claim modest and accurate: hallucinations are normally individual, and it is the CONJUNCTION of facts that resists a natural account — not a flat claim that group visions are psychologically impossible. For depth, point to the essay.","from":["library/minimalfacts.html","library/emptytomb.html","docs/book-research/case-for-the-resurrection-of-jesus.md"]},{"id":"resurrection-paul-james","topic":"The conversions of Paul (enemy) and James (sceptic)","tags":["resurrection","paul","james","conversion","persecutor","sceptic","hostile witness","damascus","disciples","witnesses","enemies","converted","changed"],"framing":"Two conversions carry unusual weight because they are hostile witnesses, not friendly ones. Paul was actively persecuting the church — not grieving, not expecting a messiah — when he became convinced he had seen the risen Jesus; he converted on what he took to be first-hand evidence, not someone else's testimony. James, Jesus' own brother, was an unbeliever during the ministry (an embarrassing admission the Gospels would have no motive to invent) yet became a leader of the Jerusalem church and, by non-Christian attestation (Josephus), was martyred. Neither man fits the profile a grief-hallucination or wish-fulfilment theory requires. Keep it to 'became convinced he had seen him' / 'sincerely believed,' never 'proven.' Concede their sincerity and the facts, never the sceptic's frame. For the sources, point to the Paul-conversion essay.","from":["library/paulconv.html","docs/book-research/case-for-the-resurrection-of-jesus.md"]},{"id":"resurrection-was-jesus-dead","topic":"Did Jesus really die? (the swoon / apparent-death theory)","tags":["resurrection","swoon","apparent death","crucifixion","did jesus die","faint","survive the cross","died on the cross","really dead","only fainted","swoon theory"],"framing":"'Maybe Jesus only fainted and later revived' (the swoon theory) turns on a distinction worth making explicit: it GRANTS that Jesus was crucified — which is about as well-attested as anything in ancient history, conceded even by hostile sources (Josephus, Tacitus) and by sceptics like John Dominic Crossan, who calls the crucifixion 'as sure as anything historical can ever be' — and disputes only that the crucifixion actually killed him. That is the implausible part. Roman crucifixion was a reliable method of execution, and the idea that a severely flogged, crucified man could survive it, escape a sealed tomb unaided, and then persuade his followers he had risen as the Lord of life asks far more of the evidence than simply concluding he died. Handle the physical specifics soberly, not gruesomely, and don't lean the whole case on any single medical study. For the detail, point to the essay.","from":["library/minimalfacts.html","docs/book-research/case-for-the-resurrection-of-jesus.md"]},{"id":"deity-of-christ-nt","topic":"Did Jesus claim to be God? (the New Testament case)","tags":["deity of christ","is jesus god","did jesus claim to be god","son of god","divine","worship jesus","my lord and my god","incarnation","jesus divinity","jesus never said he was god"],"framing":"'Did Jesus actually claim to be God?' Don't rest it on one proof-text a sceptic can re-read — make the CUMULATIVE case. Across the New Testament's twenty-seven documents by independent authors, Jesus is repeatedly included within the unique identity of the one God of Israel (Richard Bauckham's phrase): he receives worship, forgives sins, shares the divine name, throne, and works of creation, and is confessed by a strict monotheist like Thomas as 'My Lord and my God' (John 20:28). Be precise about the claim and its limits: the New Testament does not yet use the later fourth- and fifth-century vocabulary of 'one essence in three persons' or 'two natures' — the honest thesis is that the raw data the creeds later organized is already present, distributed across the whole canon, so the developed doctrine is the faithful articulation of the texts, not a later imposition on them. Hold the full deity AND the full humanity of Christ together. For the wide-angle case, point to the essay.","from":["library/jesus_as_god_nt.html"]},{"id":"trinity-not-a-contradiction","topic":"Is the Trinity a contradiction? (one God, three persons)","tags":["trinity","contradiction","three gods","tritheism","one god three persons","how can god be three and one","is the trinity logical","1+1+1","triune"],"framing":"'Isn't the Trinity a contradiction — three Gods, or 1+1+1=1?' It would be a contradiction only if it claimed God is one person AND three persons, or one God AND three Gods, in the SAME respect. It does not. The doctrine is one BEING (one 'what') existing as three PERSONS (three 'whos') — Father, Son, and Holy Spirit — each fully and equally God, co-equal and co-eternal, yet really distinct. Different categories, so there is no formal contradiction to answer. Guard the boundary in BOTH directions: press the oneness until the three are mere masks and you have modalism; press the threeness until you have three separate beings and you have tritheism; split God into three parts and you have partialism; demote the Son and you have subordinationism/Arianism — all rejected. The popular analogies (egg, water, shamrock) each tend to model one of those very errors, so use them cautiously if at all. This is the shared creedal ground of Catholics, Orthodox, and Protestants — defend it fully and confidently. For depth, point to the essay.","from":["library/analogies.html","library/relations.html"]},{"id":"fine-tuning-design","topic":"Does cosmic fine-tuning point to a designer?","tags":["fine tuning","design","designer","constants","multiverse","cosmological constant","universe designed","physics god","anthropic","tuned for life"],"framing":"On cosmic fine-tuning, keep strictly apart the two things a sceptic tends to blur. That the fundamental constants and initial conditions sit in narrow life-permitting ranges is MEASURED PHYSICS, largely uncontested across worldviews — concede it freely. That this POINTS TO A DESIGNER is a philosophical INFERENCE, and a contested one — never say 'scientists agree the universe is designed.' The argument is that among the live explanations of the data — brute chance, physical necessity, a multiverse, or design — design has the better claim; the multiverse is the main serious rival and should be engaged on its merits, not waved away. State the data carefully, argue the inference honestly, and don't overstate what physics alone establishes. For the full case with the objections answered, point to the fine-tuning essay.","from":["library/finetuning.html"]},{"id":"kalam-cause-of-universe","topic":"The kalam argument — did the universe need a cause?","tags":["kalam","cause of the universe","first cause","did the universe begin","big bang god","what caused god","everything has a cause","beginning of the universe","why is there something"],"framing":"The kalam cosmological argument runs: whatever BEGINS to exist has a cause; the universe began to exist; therefore the universe has a cause. The single most important precision — get it right or the argument collapses — is that premise one is NOT 'everything has a cause.' That careless version invites the retort 'then what caused God?' The argument concerns only things that BEGIN to exist; a being that never began needs no cause, so the question does not apply to God (and the point is not special pleading — it is what the premise actually says). Defend premise two (the universe began) from both the philosophical problems with a literally infinite past and the cosmological evidence for a beginning, conceding honestly where the science is provisional. The argument reaches a beginningless, timeless, spaceless, immaterial, enormously powerful cause — not, by itself, the whole of Christian theism; that is a further step, argued separately. For the depth, point to the kalam essay.","from":["library/kalam.html"]},{"id":"pagan-myths-copycat","topic":"Was Jesus copied from pagan dying-and-rising gods?","tags":["pagan myths","copycat","osiris","mithras","horus","dying and rising gods","borrowed","mystery religions","jesus copied","zeitgeist","adonis"],"framing":"'Isn't Jesus just copied from pagan dying-and-rising gods like Osiris, Mithras, or Horus?' No — the alleged parallels dissolve when you read the actual sources, and the strongest voices saying so are secular historians of religion, not apologists (e.g. Jonathan Z. Smith of Chicago, who judged the whole 'dying-and-rising god' category largely a misnomer built on late and ambiguous texts). Where genuine dying-and-rising cases are even claimed, they tend to be seasonal vegetation deities tied to the crop cycle in a timeless mythic 'once upon a time' (and even these fit poorly — Osiris, for one, is revived only to rule the underworld, not restored to earthly life) — a categorically different claim from a named man, under a named governor (Pontius Pilate), in a known city, said to have risen once, bodily, never to die again. Mithras and Horus in particular simply don't match the story once you check the sources rather than the memes. Represent these religions accurately and without mockery — the point is that the parallels are late, loose, and ill-fitting, not that other faiths are contemptible. For the detail, point to the essay.","from":["answers/was-jesus-copied-from-pagan-myths","library/uniqueness.html"]},{"id":"problem-of-evil","topic":"The problem of evil and suffering","tags":["problem of evil","suffering","why does god allow suffering","pain","theodicy","free will defense","plantinga","evil and god","if god is good why","natural disasters","why do bad things happen"],"framing":"The problem of evil is first a WOUND, not a puzzle — begin there. Before any argument, say plainly that no argument removes the pain, and that the church's first calling toward a suffering person is presence, not explanation (to sit in the ashes, as Job's friends first did rightly for seven days). Then, carefully: the LOGICAL version (that God and evil cannot both exist) is widely regarded as answered — Alvin Plantinga's free-will DEFENSE shows there is no contradiction in God permitting evil for goods that outweigh it. Note what that is: a defense (it shows the belief is consistent), NOT a complete theodicy that explains every particular evil. The EVIDENTIAL version (that the sheer scale of suffering makes God unlikely) is harder, and should be conceded as such — we do not possess a tidy account of why each evil is permitted, and honest acknowledgement here is stronger than a forced answer. Keep the register pastoral, and point to the essay for the fuller treatment.","from":["library/evil.html","answers/why-does-god-allow-suffering"]},{"id":"moral-argument","topic":"The moral argument for God","tags":["moral argument","morality","objective morality","right and wrong","where does morality come from","can atheists be moral","moral values","moral duties","ground of morality","without god","is anything really wrong"],"framing":"The moral argument runs: if God does not exist, objective moral values and duties do not exist; objective moral values and duties DO exist; therefore God exists. Two precisions decide whether it lands. First — never skip this — the claim is about the GROUND of morality, not about who is moral: it is NOT that atheists cannot be good, cannot tell right from wrong, or are wicked (they plainly can and do). The claim is that real, mind-independent moral OBLIGATIONS need a foundation beyond human preference; without God there is only opinion. Second, keep William Lane Craig's distinction: values concern good and bad, duties concern right and wrong, and 'objective' means independent of human opinion — the point is not that moral views vary across cultures (they do) but that some things are really wrong regardless of opinion. The live debate is over premise one — whether objective moral duties could be grounded in anything other than God (premise two, that such duties exist, is comparatively common ground) — never over whether unbelievers behave morally. Point to the essay for the depth.","from":["library/moral.html","answers/what-is-the-moral-argument-for-god"]},{"id":"same-god-islam","topic":"Do Muslims and Christians worship the same God?","tags":["same god","do muslims and christians worship the same god","allah","worship the same god","islam same god","is allah the same god","muslims christians god"],"framing":"'Do Muslims and Christians worship the same God?' Answer: no — and the difference is not a detail at the edges, it is WHO God is. The Christian God is eternally Father, Son, and Holy Spirit; the Son is not an add-on to God but essential to who he has always been. Subtract him and you are not describing a simpler version of the same God — you are describing someone else. So do NOT say Christianity and Islam 'worship the same God'; that concedes the frame. Hold charity and clarity together: a Muslim sincerely seeking the one Creator is reaching, in that instinct, toward what is real — but reaching is not arriving, and sincerity is not the same as worshipping the Triune God as he actually is. Concede the person's sincerity and the shared instinct toward one Creator; never concede that the two describe the same God. Represent Islam accurately, not as a caricature. Point to the essay for the fuller case.","from":["answers/do-muslims-and-christians-worship-the-same-god","library/islam-jesusmuslim.html"]},{"id":"mormons-jws-christian","topic":"Are Mormons / Jehovah's Witnesses Christians?","tags":["are mormons christians","are jehovahs witnesses christians","mormon","jehovahs witness","lds","latter-day saint","watchtower","is a mormon a christian","cult","new religious movement"],"framing":"'Are Mormons / Jehovah's Witnesses Christians?' On the question that actually defines the word — the doctrine of God confessed in the Nicene Creed and shared by Catholics, Orthodox, and Protestants — the answer is no, and LEAD with that. The issue is NOT sincerity, nor how closely someone studies the Bible, nor a mere label: it is the identity of God and of Christ. Latter-day Saint teaching departs from the creedal doctrine of God at the root; Jehovah's Witness teaching denies the full deity of Christ (treating the Son as God's first creature, not God the Son) — and both groups openly affirm the difference themselves. So concede their sincerity and that they use the same vocabulary — but never concede the theology, and never let the answer drift into 'well, in a warmer sense they are Christians too.' Represent each group's actual teaching accurately and without contempt. Point to the essay for the specifics.","from":["answers/are-mormons-christians","answers/are-jehovahs-witnesses-christians"]},{"id":"jesus-good-teacher-only","topic":"Was Jesus just a good moral teacher?","tags":["good teacher","just a teacher","good moral teacher","good man","lewis trilemma","liar lunatic lord","wise teacher","only a prophet","jesus just a man","great moral teacher"],"framing":"'Wasn't Jesus just a good moral teacher?' It sounds respectful, but it is the one option his own claims do not leave open. A merely good teacher does not accept worship, claim to forgive sins, and share God's own name — unless the claims are true. C.S. Lewis's trilemma puts it sharply: someone saying what Jesus said is a liar, a lunatic, or Lord — not merely a wise human teacher, because wise teachers do not make themselves the center of their own message. But note the honest gap Lewis left: the modern objection is not 'liar or lunatic,' it is a FOURTH option — that Jesus never made these claims and they were legends added later. So the trilemma is not self-contained; it must be paired with the historical case that Jesus really did make such claims (the early sources, the enemies' hostile reaction). Make that pairing rather than leaning on the trilemma alone. Point to the deity-of-Christ case for the depth.","from":["answers/was-jesus-just-a-good-moral-teacher","library/jesus_as_god_nt.html"]}];
